    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>It's the National Guard</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Edwin Andrews letter says sending National Guard to fight civil war in Iraq is contradictory to its main purpose of responding to natural disasters and other emergencies in US (April 10 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re your April 10 news article about the possible deployment of 13,000 National Guard members to Iraq:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re your April 10 news article about the possible deployment of 13,000 National Guard members to Iraq:</p>
        <p>Perhaps this administration should rename the National Guard the ''International Guard.''</p>
        <p>Sending large numbers of National Guard members to fight in a civil war thousands of miles away is contradictory to the main purposes of the National Guard.</p>
        <p>It is also shocking that the only way these units can obtain sufficient equipment for training is the prospect of international deployment.</p>
        <p>If we care about the job they are to do, shouldn't all units have enough equipment? Or is it more important that the rich pay less taxes?</p>
        <p>Finally, the purpose of the National Guard has been to respond to natural disasters or other emergencies in this country. What will we do if we are hit with another devastating natural disaster like Hurricane Katrina?</p>
        <p>This article is a sad commentary on the unwillingness of politicians to make difficult decisions, but it is quite a statement about the courage and patriotism of these National Guard members.</p>
        <p>Edwin Andrews  Malden, Mass., April 10, 2007</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
